{"term": "1972", "caseName": "Norwood v. Harrison", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/1972/72-77", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - February 21, 1973", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/15659", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- arguments in Number 72-77, Norwood against Harrison.", "start": 0, "stop": 7.125, "duration": 7.13}, {"text": "Mr. Allain.", "start": 7.125, "stop": 9.206, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice may it please the Court.", "start": 9.206, "stop": 12.447, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "I think we should first realize what we do have in this lawsuit and what we do not have in the lawsuit.", "start": 12.447, "stop": 18.953, "duration": 6.51}, {"text": "I direct the Court's or invite the Court's attention to the appendix at page 19 which contains the complaint of a lawsuit.", "start": 18.953, "stop": 30.148, "duration": 11.2}, {"text": "The second paragraph thereof the plaintiff seek a temporary restraining order and preliminary and permanent injunction, enjoining the defendants from providing or permitting the distribution or sale of state purchased or owned textbooks to private, racially segregated schools or academies.", "start": 30.148, "stop": 53.111, "duration": 22.96}, {"text": "This case is a fine drawn legal question.", "start": 53.111, "stop": 57.6, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "It is not a question of whether or not the 170 challenged academies have a racially motivated admission policy.", "start": 57.6, "stop": 69.877, "duration": 12.28}, {"text": "It is one which deals basically with whether or not the State of Mississippi can lend text books to the pupils attending racially segregated private academies regardless, regardless of how they got that way.", "start": 69.877, "stop": 90.534, "duration": 20.66}, {"text": "Now if the Court will look at the appendix, at page 22 in which the relief requested is that before textbooks can be allowed to, here they say, “Private schools and all students,” there must first be a showing to the District Court that the private school is racially integrated both as to students and faculty and in a conjunctive, has not have the effect of frustrating or impeding the establishment of racially integrated public schools.", "start": 90.534, "stop": 128.948, "duration": 38.41}, {"text": "Now that, Your Honors is a burden that no private school in the United States that I believe, I know of could carry which shows a fine line which this particular case takes.", "start": 128.948, "stop": 143.473, "duration": 14.53}, {"text": "They are saying they won’t relieve to this extent, unless the private schools now can show that they have an open enrollment admission policy, but that they must be racially integrated both in faculty and in students.", "start": 143.473, "stop": 161.575, "duration": 18.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let me make sure of what your position is.", "start": 161.575, "stop": 167.091, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "Let's assume that you do have some schools where -- that do not have an open admission policy, what about that?", "start": 167.091, "stop": 174.991, "duration": 7.9}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the Court please, I do not think that is a question in this lawsuit but if we did have that --", "start": 174.991, "stop": 179.961, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why is it not the question in this lawsuit?", "start": 179.961, "stop": 181.477, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because the lawsuit was drafted and framed by the plaintiffs and is shown by the appellants brief, the question before this Court does not deal, does not deal, does not deal with what the race -- what the admission policy of the school is, it is on the theory --", "start": 181.477, "stop": 197.996, "duration": 16.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, don’t you think that question fairly subsumes the idea that the -- at the very least the Equal Protection Clause is violated in connection with those schools, if any which do have a closed admission policy?", "start": 197.996, "stop": 213.395, "duration": 15.4}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor I don’t, except the reason that in the --", "start": 213.395, "stop": 215.464, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well let’s assume that we didn’t agree with you and that it does subsume that question?", "start": 215.464, "stop": 221.229, "duration": 5.77}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "If it will subsume that question I think we would still be on solid ground with the teachings of these Court cases in Allen and the Cochran case.", "start": 221.229, "stop": 229.544, "duration": 8.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "So even with respect to schools if any that has a closed admission policy?", "start": 229.544, "stop": 234.939, "duration": 5.39}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is right Your Honor because it is aid to the pupil and not to the school the same rationale of the Allen case, the Cochran case out of Louisiana, 1930 dealing with textbook.", "start": 234.939, "stop": 244.955, "duration": 10.02}, {"text": "The Allen case by Your Honor you wrote that of -- of that opinion in 1960.", "start": 244.955, "stop": 250.528, "duration": 5.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you find anything in the Allen case that indicated the schools there had a closed admission policy?", "start": 250.528, "stop": 254.929, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, we did not Your Honor.", "start": 254.929, "stop": 256.512, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "But the rationale there did not deal with the -- whether or not the admission policy was closed or open, the rationale as I understand Allen and I hate to debate with the author of the opinion but that the mere fact that it went to the pupil and not to the student.", "start": 256.512, "stop": 270.031, "duration": 13.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, if you read -- if you read the argument further advanced in Lemon against Kurtzman.", "start": 270.031, "stop": 274.242, "duration": 4.21}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor you did.", "start": 274.242, "stop": 275.555, "duration": 1.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "About closed admission policy?", "start": 275.555, "stop": 276.646, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 276.646, "stop": 277.661, "duration": 1.01}, {"text": "But I -- the rationale of the Allen case if we understand, the Cochran case, Mississippi’s Chance case, the -- all the cases that -- the transportation case is that it is aid to the pupil and the student or the parent and not to the school.", "start": 277.661, "stop": 293.054, "duration": 15.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 293.054, "stop": 293.397, "duration": 0.34}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, I say that I do not to believe the issues framed here or is brought as Your Honor addresses himself for the simple reason that there is no proof in this case.", "start": 293.397, "stop": 303.576, "duration": 10.18}, {"text": "No attempted proof by the plaintiff to show what the particular admission policy was of the 107 academies.", "start": 303.576, "stop": 313.024, "duration": 9.45}, {"text": "In fact, the proof is just the opposite shown by cross-examination by the defendants that that did have, the 107 have an open enrollment policy.", "start": 313.024, "stop": 323.631, "duration": 10.61}, {"text": "It is either on the minutes, it is oral, verbal and sometimes it went so far as be advertised in the newspapers.", "start": 323.631, "stop": 333.152, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "So I think from the fact that the case in the lower court was not tried on that issue.", "start": 333.152, "stop": 338.494, "duration": 5.34}, {"text": "There was no attempt to show by the plaintiffs that that was a closed admission policy.", "start": 338.494, "stop": 344.482, "duration": 5.99}, {"text": "This case is drawn on the same fine lines of the tuition cases in which the courts held that the mere fact that they were racially segregated, not how they got there, but that is a different rationale, a different principle.", "start": 344.482, "stop": 360.329, "duration": 15.85}, {"text": "For the simple reason in the tuition cases, the Coffey I, Coffey II, the Poindexter cases, Griffin case found that the State of Mississippi and the State of Louisiana and Virginia were operating not necessarily racially discriminatory white academies, but they had in one -- they're still operating a dual school system because in that case, under I guess the under the rationale of Burton case, the sifting of the facts and the circumstances show that they were actually in partnership with the private schools.", "start": 360.329, "stop": 398.015, "duration": 37.69}, {"text": "The tuition was the basic income of the private schools.", "start": 398.015, "stop": 402.403, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "So instead of having an Allen case or instead of even having a Burton case, you had a Brown and Griffin case which did not depend upon a finding by the Court that there was an open or a closed admission policies for -- as the private school were concerned because of the mere fact that they were predominantly white, put the State of Mississippi and Louisiana in operating a dual school system again under the freedom of choice.", "start": 402.403, "stop": 430.682, "duration": 28.28}, {"text": "Now we say to the Court that we think that this case regardless of how it is taken is controlled by the line of cases of Allen and Cochran, the transportation and textbook cases and the plaintiffs try to get past the rationale and holding in those cases by saying, “Well this is a Fourteenth Amendment case and not a First Amendment.”", "start": 430.682, "stop": 454.456, "duration": 23.77}, {"text": "I say to the Court that the First Amendment, the establishment clause of the First Amendment, now I know Mr. Chief Justice has spoke in the Tilton about the internal tension between the establishment clause and the exercise clause.", "start": 454.456, "stop": 468.139, "duration": 13.68}, {"text": "But the establishment clause has been held by this Court as absolute.", "start": 468.139, "stop": 474.639, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "The exercise clause is not absolute as to actions of individuals and that’s in the Jacobs case which allowed inoculations and I think the Prince case against Massachusetts was the labor, the child labor.", "start": 474.639, "stop": 489.225, "duration": 14.59}, {"text": "But you are talking about an absolute in the establishment clause and therefore we submit to the Court that the measuring stick for the establishment clause of the First Amendment is more stringent and more stringent than that of the Fourteenth Amendment whose contours as this Court has said have not been concretely established to allow for flexibility.", "start": 489.225, "stop": 513.188, "duration": 23.96}, {"text": "The measuring stick apparently in the Fourteenth Amendment cases would be the Burton case where we must sift the facts and look at the circumstances to see whether or not a state has put itself in partnership with the academies.", "start": 513.188, "stop": 528.947, "duration": 15.76}, {"text": "And counsel and the plaintiffs go further and say “Yes” but you are not controlled by Burton for the simple reason.", "start": 528.947, "stop": 534.502, "duration": 5.55}, {"text": "Green and Swan say that the State of Mississippi has an affirmative duty.", "start": 534.502, "stop": 540.941, "duration": 6.44}, {"text": "So it is actually not the Fourteenth Amendment per se which the plaintiffs are riding in this particular case.", "start": 540.941, "stop": 547.36, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "It’s the First Amendment with the gloss put up on it by Swan and Green upon any state which has had a dual school system.", "start": 547.36, "stop": 556.796, "duration": 9.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "You referred to transportation a few moments ago, does the state furnish transportation to the students of these private schools?", "start": 556.796, "stop": 565.731, "duration": 8.93}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor, there is no, the only benefits given by the state to any individual, enrolled in a private school are the textbooks.", "start": 565.731, "stop": 577.733, "duration": 12}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, could the state in your view lawfully furnish transportation to the students in this private schools, assuming now, limiting my question to those private schools that had an exclusion policy?", "start": 577.733, "stop": 593.685, "duration": 15.95}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that they could Your Honor.", "start": 593.685, "stop": 596.041, "duration": 2.36}, {"text": "Under the rationale of the New Jersey case which held -- of course the Everson case which it held that transportation did not violate the establishment clause in the New Jersey case.", "start": 596.041, "stop": 607.32, "duration": 11.28}, {"text": "But the affirmative duty doctrine is -- has never been completely defined by this Court.", "start": 607.32, "stop": 614.635, "duration": 7.31}, {"text": "How far does a state have to go in order to do away with any, anything which interferes as the plaintiffs say that the academies interfere with the unitary school system in Mississippi.", "start": 614.635, "stop": 630.708, "duration": 16.07}, {"text": "That taken to its logical conclusion and the plaintiff’s are asking and are saying that the state can give no aid.", "start": 630.708, "stop": 640.819, "duration": 10.11}, {"text": "Now that taken to its illogical logical extension would be that they must cut off water, sewer, electricity.", "start": 640.819, "stop": 649.068, "duration": 8.25}, {"text": "Now, I know this sounds absurd because Mr. Justice Rehnquist in the Moose Lodge case and Mr. Chief Justice in the Lemon case and Mr. Brennan in the concurring of the Lemon case stated that this were benefits which could flow to private schools, to church schools or anything else.", "start": 649.068, "stop": 672.145, "duration": 23.08}, {"text": "But if we take this affirmative duty that the plaintiffs are tempting to urge upon the Court, then how far is it necessary for the State of Mississippi or Louisiana or any other state to go to get rid of what they say are the private segregated schools regardless of how they get there which is interfering --", "start": 672.145, "stop": 695.185, "duration": 23.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) would your answer be stop giving money for textbooks?", "start": 695.185, "stop": 698.663, "duration": 3.48}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, maybe it could stop there, I would not, what I am saying to the Court --", "start": 698.663, "stop": 702.855, "duration": 4.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that what's in this case?", "start": 702.855, "stop": 704.042, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is what is in this case, but that is not --", "start": 704.042, "stop": 705.546, "duration": 1.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Doesn’t have anything to do with sewers and water?", "start": 705.546, "stop": 708.418, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor what is requested in this case does because of the rationale and what this case would stand for.", "start": 708.418, "stop": 714.354, "duration": 5.94}, {"text": "In the affirmative duty --", "start": 714.354, "stop": 715.507, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don’t think it could be written narrow enough to be limited to textbooks?", "start": 715.507, "stop": 719.746, "duration": 4.24}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor I do not because --", "start": 719.746, "stop": 720.938, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap)", "start": 720.938, "stop": 721.756, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- then you would get into transportation and then you would get into whether or not private schools should be charted in Mississippi.", "start": 721.756, "stop": 727.601, "duration": 5.85}, {"text": "You would get into whether or not that the universities of Mississippi should accept the credits from these private schools.", "start": 727.601, "stop": 735.283, "duration": 7.68}, {"text": "You would get in to all types of aid, if you want to call it aid which is being given to private schools in which they are participating in.", "start": 735.283, "stop": 744.515, "duration": 9.23}, {"text": "I don’t see any of decision in this case could be so limited.", "start": 744.515, "stop": 749.614, "duration": 5.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I thought you started your argument with saying that this a very narrow case involving a very narrow issue and you read on page 19 about textbooks.", "start": 749.614, "stop": 762.659, "duration": 13.04}, {"text": "Are you now saying that it’s broader than that?", "start": 762.659, "stop": 765.061, "duration": 2.4}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor I said it had a fine line drawn as far as a factual situation and because of that fine line as to factual situation, it would make any decision adverse to the state a broad holding.", "start": 765.061, "stop": 779.978, "duration": 14.92}, {"text": "The fine line of facts makes the holding broader than is the facts were brought up then you might be able to this -- to limit the holding.", "start": 779.978, "stop": 790.71, "duration": 10.73}, {"text": "For the simple reason that they are asking for an underlining that any aid given to the 107 private schools should be cutoff and when I say any aid, let us take for instance a really absurdity --", "start": 790.71, "stop": 805.61, "duration": 14.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could you show me that in the complaint, where they say any aid?", "start": 805.61, "stop": 809.337, "duration": 3.73}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor I’m not too sure that it’s in the complaint, but it permeates throughout the --", "start": 809.337, "stop": 813.755, "duration": 4.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I thought you started your argument that we were limited to the complaint.", "start": 813.755, "stop": 818.355, "duration": 4.6}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor I did not intend to say we were limited to the complaint.", "start": 818.355, "stop": 821.445, "duration": 3.09}, {"text": "I merely intended to say that the factual situation is framed by the state.", "start": 821.445, "stop": 826.665, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "But, well for your benefit it’s limited to the complaint and where is your benefit to go beyond the complaint, you go beyond it.", "start": 826.665, "stop": 832.992, "duration": 6.33}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor I was -- the relief -- now in the relief, the relief does state.", "start": 832.992, "stop": 837.332, "duration": 4.34}, {"text": "As you read in the relief it does go further and talks about until racially integrated both as to students and faculty.", "start": 837.332, "stop": 846.694, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "That is on page 22 of the appendix.", "start": 846.694, "stop": 851.059, "duration": 4.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Perhaps you would stand not all of the (Inaudible)", "start": 851.059, "stop": 857.701, "duration": 6.64}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor it is speaking here that unless --", "start": 857.701, "stop": 860.277, "duration": 2.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 860.277, "stop": 866.726, "duration": 6.45}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor that is the request at this time.", "start": 866.726, "stop": 871.605, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "It is not -- is not beyond the scope to see the next lawsuit that would be before this Court citing this case as authority.", "start": 871.605, "stop": 880.015, "duration": 8.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "We don't have the next lawsuit, we have this one.", "start": 880.015, "stop": 882.577, "duration": 2.56}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor what I’m saying to the Court is though because of the fine factual situation the decision in this Court would precipitate immediately another lawsuit as to any other aid which was given to these private schools.", "start": 882.577, "stop": 899.146, "duration": 16.57}, {"text": "Plus the fact that if and I think Mr. Chief -- Mr. Justice Stewart said yesterday that maybe this could go back and what the determination have to be made as to each particular school, it could not be made on this record sir.", "start": 899.146, "stop": 913.616, "duration": 14.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did you say a minute ago that there was no aid other than textbooks given to private schools in Mississippi, did you say that?", "start": 913.616, "stop": 922.81, "duration": 9.19}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "I said the only aid that were given to students attending private schools in Mississippi was the textbook.", "start": 922.81, "stop": 931.792, "duration": 8.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that’s all before us?", "start": 931.792, "stop": 934.184, "duration": 2.39}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 934.184, "stop": 934.664, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is all that’s before us?", "start": 934.664, "stop": 937.288, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is all before you in the --", "start": 937.288, "stop": 938.975, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) advice, your opinion as to what Mississippi can or cannot do in the future, do you?", "start": 938.975, "stop": 943.713, "duration": 4.74}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor I do not think and I do not want to argue with the -- Your Honor only is I do not think that it is an advisory opinion which in it -- it is an opinion in which a later suit, a later case can be built on for the simple reason of what the holding would be in this particular case that regardless of how these 107 academies came about, regardless of whether they had an open enrollment policy or not unless they were racially integrated and I don’t know how you get a private school racially integrated anywhere in America because its a choice by these pupils.", "start": 943.713, "stop": 980.18, "duration": 36.47}, {"text": "It is usually a tuition that they have to pay and the people go there because of their choice.", "start": 980.18, "stop": 984.795, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "I do not know how that anyone could carry the burden with this type of decision by the Court would establish.", "start": 984.795, "stop": 996.606, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "So we say to the Court that even under the affirmative duty doctrine as the Court addressed itself to in Swan where the courts recognized that even under this we are -- the equity power of the Court is limited in what it can do.", "start": 996.606, "stop": 1013.521, "duration": 16.91}, {"text": "That they cannot ride that doctrine to the extent of saying that these 107 schools regardless, regardless of their policy of admission, regardless of how they became into being, regardless to how they are supported, are not the pupils attending are not entitled to textbooks.", "start": 1013.521, "stop": 1033.76, "duration": 20.24}, {"text": "And remember this textbook law came into being in 1940 rather than 1942.", "start": 1033.76, "stop": 1038.457, "duration": 4.7}, {"text": "It was amended in 1942 to bring in high schools.", "start": 1038.457, "stop": 1041.417, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "It came during a depression.", "start": 1041.417, "stop": 1043.625, "duration": 2.21}, {"text": "It came with the benevolence of the state in order to help not only not just white children in Mississippi, but black and white children who were attending public and private schools.", "start": 1043.625, "stop": 1054.106, "duration": 10.48}, {"text": "In fact I dare say that the --", "start": 1054.106, "stop": 1055.505, "duration": 1.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Were there any black academies in the 1940, in Mississippi?", "start": 1055.505, "stop": 1059.121, "duration": 3.62}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "I do not know about that Your Honor, I do know that for the --", "start": 1059.121, "stop": 1062.551, "duration": 3.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1062.551, "stop": 1065.756, "duration": 3.21}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor I said as to public, its public education --", "start": 1065.756, "stop": 1068.134, "duration": 2.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh!", "start": 1068.134, "stop": 1068.177, "duration": 0.04}, {"text": "Alright.", "start": 1068.177, "stop": 1068.386, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the typically, textbook went to public and private schools and I dare say that the black community, knowing Mississippi as I do that the effect upon the pocketbook was of more value probably at that time to the black parent than it was to the white parent.", "start": 1068.386, "stop": 1084.814, "duration": 16.43}, {"text": "Now the inconsistency in the argument made by the plaintiffs is the fact that they want to exclude from this holding, one that catholic schools in Mississippi, why?", "start": 1084.814, "stop": 1097.707, "duration": 12.89}, {"text": "Why do they have something like 12,000 students, 10,000 whites and well, two to two-and-half black?", "start": 1097.707, "stop": 1108.443, "duration": 10.74}, {"text": "There is no showing that they are integrated.", "start": 1108.443, "stop": 1111.401, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "In fact the record will probably show they're predominantly segregated.", "start": 1111.401, "stop": 1116.182, "duration": 4.78}, {"text": "So if this type of academy is what they are oppressing on the Court, what makes any difference whether or not it’s the catholic schools?", "start": 1116.182, "stop": 1126.03, "duration": 9.85}, {"text": "They had excluded two, I think, predominant black schools.", "start": 1126.03, "stop": 1130.339, "duration": 4.31}, {"text": "Why exclude them, aren't they taking out of the system pupils who should be back into public schools?", "start": 1130.339, "stop": 1137.155, "duration": 6.82}, {"text": "They’ve excluded other academies, I think five other academies.", "start": 1137.155, "stop": 1141.581, "duration": 4.43}, {"text": "So why is there an inclusion to be consistent with the principle that the plaintiffs are attempting to urge upon this Court?", "start": 1141.581, "stop": 1151.543, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "These academies, these academies are doing the same thing as the 107 academies would say are trying -- they challenge in this particular lawsuit.", "start": 1151.543, "stop": 1161.021, "duration": 9.48}, {"text": "We say to the court that the statute was enacted in 1940 without any racial motives.", "start": 1161.021, "stop": 1168.377, "duration": 7.36}, {"text": "It in no way established any dual school system and it no way established any racially segregated private schools.", "start": 1168.377, "stop": 1176.672, "duration": 8.3}, {"text": "It has been even handedly executed throughout the years.", "start": 1176.672, "stop": 1183.285, "duration": 6.61}, {"text": "I would further say to the Court that there is one finding by this Court, by the District Court which we think that unless it's manifestly wrong, this Court should affirm and this Court I think has been on record since the Brown decision in saying the District Court and the trial court is a court that must look at the factual situation.", "start": 1183.285, "stop": 1204.946, "duration": 21.66}, {"text": "This Court recently said in the Right case, gave great weight to the findings of fact by the District Court and one of the findings in that case, the third finding I believe said that we look at the timing, when was this new school system created?", "start": 1204.946, "stop": 1222.31, "duration": 17.36}, {"text": "There’s no timing problem in this particular case because it was way back in 1940.", "start": 1222.31, "stop": 1229.086, "duration": 6.78}, {"text": "The District Court found in its opinion that since the issuance of free textbooks to students attending private schools has failed to defeat the establishment of a statewide unitary school system in Mississippi and since plaintiffs are themselves receiving their free textbook, there is serious question as to whether plaintiffs are threatened with the irreparable injury which is requisite to injunctive relief.", "start": 1229.086, "stop": 1256.523, "duration": 27.44}, {"text": "Further the Court found there is no showing that any child enrolled in private schools, is deprived of free textbooks would withdraw from private school and subsequently enroll into public schools now unitary.", "start": 1256.523, "stop": 1271.739, "duration": 15.22}, {"text": "Further there is a finding by the Court in the evidence in the lower court, I mean in the depositions that the withdrawal from the pupils of this particular aid would not in anyway which is just $6.00 a year per pupil substantially effect the 107 private schools which are under attack in this particular lawsuit.", "start": 1271.739, "stop": 1297.179, "duration": 25.44}, {"text": "We say to the Court in closing that we feel that the opinion of the District Court is bottomed on the facts in that particular case and the law has been the teachings of this Court.", "start": 1297.179, "stop": 1308.577, "duration": 11.4}, {"text": "And that even in the two Poindexter cases which this Court affirmed, Judge Wisdom speaking for the District Court in similar situations in Louisiana that had a dual school system in tuition cases, distinguished those particular cases from textbooks and free luncheon and the other benevolent gifts that had been given to charitable and educational institutions throughout the years.", "start": 1308.577, "stop": 1337.198, "duration": 28.62}, {"text": "We say to the Court we think this judgment of the District Court should be affirmed.", "start": 1337.198, "stop": 1341.753, "duration": 4.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Lewis F. Powell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Allain, I think the record shows that there are 534,000 pupils in the public schools in Mississippi.", "start": 1341.753, "stop": 1351.553, "duration": 9.8}, {"text": "Does the record show the breakdown as between whites and blacks among that 534,000, what percentage?", "start": 1351.553, "stop": 1363.08, "duration": 11.53}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don’t recall Your Honor the percentage.", "start": 1363.08, "stop": 1365.042, "duration": 1.96}, {"text": "I do recall there was a thousand different schools involved in it and only 35,000 in the private school, but I’m not sure of the particular breakdown of the -- population of Mississippi breakdown is something like 60:40 of the 1970 census or 62:38.", "start": 1365.042, "stop": 1386.004, "duration": 20.96}, {"text": "I am not --", "start": 1386.004, "stop": 1386.089, "duration": 0.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Lewis F. Powell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s the total population?", "start": 1386.089, "stop": 1387.293, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "William A. Allain", "textObjs": [{"text": "Total population breakdown white to black.", "start": 1387.293, "stop": 1390.197, "duration": 2.9}, {"text": "I would think that the school enrollment maybe somewhat above that.", "start": 1390.197, "stop": 1394.212, "duration": 4.02}, {"text": "It might be a 60:40 or 55:45.", "start": 1394.212, "stop": 1400.376, "duration": 6.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you Mr. Allain.", "start": 1400.376, "stop": 1404.366, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "Mr. Leventhal you have about 10 minutes left.", "start": 1404.366, "stop": 1407.3, "duration": 2.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) Your Honor.", "start": 1407.3, "stop": 1408.69, "duration": 1.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have a question.", "start": 1408.69, "stop": 1410.163, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir?", "start": 1410.163, "stop": 1410.645, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask you, referring to page -- to the complaint which starts on page 19 of the appendix in paragraph two on page 19.", "start": 1410.645, "stop": 1423.262, "duration": 12.62}, {"text": "You said I -- what you're seeking which is a temporary restraining order on -- to prevent the sale or distribution to private racially segregated schools on the counties and then over on page 22 when you set down the -- your prayer for relief, you were asked for an injunction against the distribution of textbooks to students in schools unless those schools first established that the private school is racially integrated both as to students and faculty.", "start": 1423.262, "stop": 1456.102, "duration": 32.84}, {"text": "Now to me, those mean two separate things.", "start": 1456.102, "stop": 1459.716, "duration": 3.61}, {"text": "In other words, I should suppose that a school could in fact have nothing, but Negro children and yet not be a segregated school, but certainly it would not be an integrated school.", "start": 1459.716, "stop": 1474.43, "duration": 14.71}, {"text": "A school could in fact have nothing but white children and yet it could -- it might not be a segregated school although clearly it would not be an integrated school.", "start": 1474.43, "stop": 1484.346, "duration": 9.92}, {"text": "To me those are two quite, one is different concept from the other and they both appear here in your complaint.", "start": 1484.346, "stop": 1492.564, "duration": 8.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor we agree with that distinction the Court makes.", "start": 1492.564, "stop": 1497.2, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "However, what we’re trying to get out is subterfuge, alleged policies of open admissions.", "start": 1497.2, "stop": 1504.824, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "Now in the Green versus Kennedy case, a three-judge District Court established a series of requirements that private schools would have to satisfy in order to be eligible for tax exempt status.", "start": 1504.824, "stop": 1519.05, "duration": 14.23}, {"text": "The record shows, according to Commissioner Thrower that there are five or six academies which have qualified for tax exemption which by -- which only the most naive would consider truly open.", "start": 1519.05, "stop": 1534.8, "duration": 15.75}, {"text": "The Indianola Academy for example has satisfied the requirements of Green versus Kennedy.", "start": 1534.8, "stop": 1541.344, "duration": 6.54}, {"text": "The Indianola Academy is presently a tax exempt institution.", "start": 1541.344, "stop": 1546.269, "duration": 4.92}, {"text": "If you look at our brief, page 18, you will find an analysis of what occurred in the Indianola school district.", "start": 1546.269, "stop": 1559.464, "duration": 13.19}, {"text": "The Indianola Academy presently enrolls all white children residing in the municipality of Indianola and that academy’s enrollment tripled in the middle of the school year immediately upon this Court's decision in Alexander versus Holmes County.", "start": 1559.464, "stop": 1576.248, "duration": 16.78}, {"text": "Now we submit that what we’re really getting at here in trying to establish a standard for a private academy is to be certain that the standard of proof of open admissions is very, very high that there is no excuse for IRS’ approval of the Indianola Academy as a school with an open admissions policy.", "start": 1576.248, "stop": 1599.623, "duration": 23.38}, {"text": "According to IRS data, there are at least ten schools which are clearly segregationists which are presently tax exempt not withstanding Green versus Kennedy.", "start": 1599.623, "stop": 1623.783, "duration": 24.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "In Mississippi?", "start": 1623.783, "stop": 1624.759, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor, one of them is Indianola Academy.", "start": 1624.759, "stop": 1627.833, "duration": 3.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there's ten but you talked about a 107?", "start": 1627.833, "stop": 1631.117, "duration": 3.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "I’m saying that as long -- we agree with the Court's distinction that a school can be in fact segregated and not be segregationist.", "start": 1631.117, "stop": 1641.033, "duration": 9.92}, {"text": "At the same time, we ask the Court --", "start": 1641.033, "stop": 1641.725, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "How could be in fact all Negro or all white and yet have an open permissions policy?", "start": 1641.725, "stop": 1646.979, "duration": 5.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor, we concede that.", "start": 1646.979, "stop": 1649.029, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "And what do you understand in the meaning of racially integrated both as to students and faculty, to mean?", "start": 1649.029, "stop": 1660.975, "duration": 11.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "We view that as the standard of proof that ought to be required of the school like the Indianola Academy.", "start": 1660.975, "stop": 1666.628, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "If the Indianola Academy says it has an -- it says has an open admissions policy, it ought to prove it not with merely the policy but with an integrated student body (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1666.628, "stop": 1675.226, "duration": 8.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "As to have what, how many?", "start": 1675.226, "stop": 1677.102, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "Has to have at least some students and some faculty of both races, is that --", "start": 1677.102, "stop": 1683.263, "duration": 6.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor.", "start": 1683.263, "stop": 1683.85, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "At least some, is that your --", "start": 1683.85, "stop": 1685.059, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor.", "start": 1685.059, "stop": 1686.987, "duration": 1.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "And is this true about not only on the Indianola Academy but everyone of the private schools in the State of Mississippi, no matter how long they’ve been there and how well established their policy might be?", "start": 1686.987, "stop": 1699.235, "duration": 12.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 1699.235, "stop": 1699.426, "duration": 0.19}, {"text": "I think we’ve got to read that requirement in conjunction with other historical data.", "start": 1699.426, "stop": 1704.393, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "You see we have a network of private schools in Mississippi which were formed at a critical moment or which expanded enrollment at a critical moment and I’m referring to a standard to be applied to such academies.", "start": 1704.393, "stop": 1718.896, "duration": 14.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you using the term in your complaint at page 22, the term integrated as synonymous with desegregated, in pursuing your points with Justice Stewart as I’m not quite sure of your answer.", "start": 1718.896, "stop": 1737.2, "duration": 18.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor.", "start": 1737.2, "stop": 1737.513, "duration": 0.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, if that can be read as though the word integrated were stricken and the word desegregated were inserted, is that the way you want us to read it?", "start": 1737.513, "stop": 1747.397, "duration": 9.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor.", "start": 1747.397, "stop": 1747.833, "duration": 0.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s what you intend.", "start": 1747.833, "stop": 1749.201, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s what we requested.", "start": 1749.201, "stop": 1750.705, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "However --", "start": 1750.705, "stop": 1751.334, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the District Court held it irrelevant anyway (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1751.334, "stop": 1754.215, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor.", "start": 1754.215, "stop": 1754.564, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1754.564, "stop": 1754.768, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't that what you're objecting to, let say, the District Court said the – it doesn’t make any difference whether they have an open policy or closed policy, books can go to any school.", "start": 1754.768, "stop": 1763.272, "duration": 8.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s right.", "start": 1763.272, "stop": 1763.901, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was the holding?", "start": 1763.901, "stop": 1765.439, "duration": 1.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, that’s correct and in fact --", "start": 1765.439, "stop": 1767.214, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And now, if let’s assume we did not agree with that holding, are you asking us to say that on the other -- there on the other end of the spectrum that it's irrelevant whether any of these schools have an open admission policy?", "start": 1767.214, "stop": 1780.883, "duration": 13.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh!", "start": 1780.883, "stop": 1781.088, "duration": 0.2}, {"text": "No sir, by no means, by no means.", "start": 1781.088, "stop": 1783.436, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "Now we want to make it clear that our objective is to eliminate textbook aid to segregationist academies or segregated academies.", "start": 1783.436, "stop": 1794.568, "duration": 11.13}, {"text": "The question of what standard should be applied to determine what is a segregated academy is not essential to our lawsuit by no means.", "start": 1794.568, "stop": 1805.27, "duration": 10.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you concede the possibility that some of these schools might be able to make a showing that they had an open admissions policy?", "start": 1805.27, "stop": 1815.353, "duration": 10.08}, {"text": "I’m simply saying a possibility.", "start": 1815.353, "stop": 1816.002, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Conceive -- Yes Your Honor, conceivably.", "start": 1816.002, "stop": 1819.514, "duration": 3.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you suggesting that in order that a District Court in order to keep an order, an integration order from being frustrated that order children not to move to a private school even it had an open policy?", "start": 1819.514, "stop": 1831.319, "duration": 11.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Your Honor.", "start": 1831.319, "stop": 1832.22, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "You’re not?", "start": 1832.22, "stop": 1832.844, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir.", "start": 1832.844, "stop": 1834.049, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "We are recognizing in this litigation the right of children to attend segregated schools.", "start": 1834.049, "stop": 1840.656, "duration": 6.61}, {"text": "We are challenging their right to attend such schools with state aid.", "start": 1840.656, "stop": 1846.105, "duration": 5.45}, {"text": "That’s the thrust of our lawsuit.", "start": 1846.105, "stop": 1847.911, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Leventhal, am I correct, is there not in the record an intimation that some 41 schools did not participate in this textbook program?", "start": 1847.911, "stop": 1856.385, "duration": 8.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 1856.385, "stop": 1857.857, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that of any significance?", "start": 1857.857, "stop": 1860.611, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "Do you know why were they denominational schools for instance supported something else or what?", "start": 1860.611, "stop": 1864.931, "duration": 4.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, it’s conjectural.", "start": 1864.931, "stop": 1866.495, "duration": 1.56}, {"text": "It’s just as the defendants suggest that it means that they’re not important.", "start": 1866.495, "stop": 1869.703, "duration": 3.21}, {"text": "I could suggest one that several academies receive textbooks until recently and in anticipation of this lawsuit decided, it would be best to withdraw from the program to avoid the shock of an adverse decision.", "start": 1869.703, "stop": 1890.404, "duration": 20.7}, {"text": "So that -- why these 41 schools don’t participate would be --", "start": 1890.404, "stop": 1895.451, "duration": 5.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "What kind of a shock, not the financial one certainly?", "start": 1895.451, "stop": 1898.286, "duration": 2.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor the -- a school which grows dependent upon a particular type of aid might be reluctant to wait for a decision of this Court which they believe would be adverse to withdraw from the program.", "start": 1898.286, "stop": 1912.455, "duration": 14.17}, {"text": "In fact there’s nothing in this record which would indicate that any private school has stated that the textbooks are unnecessary or undesirable.", "start": 1912.455, "stop": 1923.771, "duration": 11.32}, {"text": "There is no evidence one way on the other on why these schools do not receive the textbooks.", "start": 1923.771, "stop": 1930.23, "duration": 6.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, thank you gentlemen.", "start": 1930.23, "stop": 1931.541, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 1931.541, "stop": 1933.116, "duration": 1.58}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - February 20, 1973", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/15772", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "We’ll hear arguments next in Number 72-77, Norwood against Harrison.", "start": 0, "stop": 21.379, "duration": 21.38}, {"text": "Mr. Leventhal, you may proceed.", "start": 21.379, "stop": 24.171, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.", "start": 24.171, "stop": 27.94, "duration": 3.77}, {"text": "Plaintiff’s appellants are black school-age children residing in Tunica County, Mississippi.", "start": 27.94, "stop": 35.476, "duration": 7.54}, {"text": "They filed this lawsuit in October of 1970 and they alleged and subsequently proved that they are attending public schools in Mississippi which were under Court order to desegregate under Alexander and under Green and that despite injunctive orders of the Northern District of Mississippi, the schools remained segregated.", "start": 35.476, "stop": 62.798, "duration": 27.32}, {"text": "They alleged further that the school -- their schools are segregated because there exists the Tunica County Institute of Learning which is a private segregated and segregationist academy located in Tunica County.", "start": 62.798, "stop": 80.529, "duration": 17.73}, {"text": "They alleged further and proved that this segregated Tunica Institute of Learning was under the laws of the State of Mississippi receiving free textbooks.", "start": 80.529, "stop": 95.091, "duration": 14.56}, {"text": "And that this textbook aid to the Private Academy of Tunica County represented unlawful support of racial discrimination and assisted in undermining public school desegregation.", "start": 95.091, "stop": 114.814, "duration": 19.72}, {"text": "They challenged the constitutionality of the Mississippi statute which required the distribution of such textbooks to the private academies of Mississippi.", "start": 114.814, "stop": 126.701, "duration": 11.89}, {"text": "Essentially, our complaint is that the State has a duty to avoid aligning itself with racial discrimination.", "start": 126.701, "stop": 137.023, "duration": 10.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "What’s the original date of enactment of this textbook statute?", "start": 137.023, "stop": 141.3, "duration": 4.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "1942, Your Honor.", "start": 141.3, "stop": 143.971, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it been materially altered since then?", "start": 143.971, "stop": 149.265, "duration": 5.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor, it has not.", "start": 149.265, "stop": 150.874, "duration": 1.61}, {"text": "It was enacted in 1942 and amended insignificantly several times.", "start": 150.874, "stop": 156.339, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "In 1942, the statute provided aid to elementary school pupils only and subsequently, the statute was extended to provide a textbook aid to high school students.", "start": 156.339, "stop": 167.792, "duration": 11.45}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What year was that though?", "start": 167.792, "stop": 169.4, "duration": 1.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe two years later, Your Honor.", "start": 169.4, "stop": 171.117, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "1944?", "start": 171.117, "stop": 171.814, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 171.814, "stop": 173.878, "duration": 2.06}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No amendments since 1954?", "start": 173.878, "stop": 176.555, "duration": 2.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "There have been amendments, Your Honor, but our research indicates that they’re not significant amendments.", "start": 176.555, "stop": 182.453, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "They’re amendments dealing with the administration of the statute.", "start": 182.453, "stop": 186.41, "duration": 3.96}, {"text": "However, along that line, there was a significant change in regulations promulgated in 1970.", "start": 186.41, "stop": 194.996, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "As pointed out in the Government’s brief amicus curiae, the textbook purchasing board in 1970 in effect, adopted a regulation which made it possible for private segregated academies of Mississippi to receive textbooks directly from the State agency.", "start": 194.996, "stop": 213.627, "duration": 18.63}, {"text": "Prior to 1970, a private academy depended upon a local school district to receive textbooks and under the Emergency School Assistance Act, such public school districts would lose federal money as they continue to provide textbooks to private academies and as a result, the State agency adopted a regulation which permitted, which indeed required that the private academies deal directly with the State textbook agency.", "start": 213.627, "stop": 249.591, "duration": 35.96}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 249.591, "stop": 251.543, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "District council -- they already have it?", "start": 251.543, "stop": 252.674, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 252.674, "stop": 254.646, "duration": 1.97}, {"text": "This is a class action and --", "start": 254.646, "stop": 257.426, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would it be today?", "start": 257.426, "stop": 258.178, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- as a result the perspective of private schools or a perspective of the present state of public and private education in Mississippi is relevant.", "start": 258.178, "stop": 270.218, "duration": 12.04}, {"text": "There is no controversy on this basic point, Your Honors.", "start": 270.218, "stop": 273.568, "duration": 3.35}, {"text": "There exists in the State of Mississippi a network of private racially segregated academies.", "start": 273.568, "stop": 279.856, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "They operate throughout the State of Mississippi and this system was formed with the purpose and has had the effect of one; undermining public school desegregation; and two, providing white students with an alternative to public school desegregation.", "start": 279.856, "stop": 298.36, "duration": 18.5}, {"text": "All of the academies are racially segregated.", "start": 298.36, "stop": 301.591, "duration": 3.23}, {"text": "All were formed concurrently with the implementation of freedom of choice plans or the implementation of Green or Alexander, decisions of this Court requiring immediate attainment of unitary school systems.", "start": 301.591, "stop": 314.332, "duration": 12.74}, {"text": "All were formed haphazardly without significant planning or resources.", "start": 314.332, "stop": 319.419, "duration": 5.09}, {"text": "I shouldn’t say all on that.", "start": 319.419, "stop": 320.71, "duration": 1.29}, {"text": "Perhaps one or two were formed on the basis of considerable planning, but the overwhelming majority of these academies were formed haphazardly without planning, without significant resources.", "start": 320.71, "stop": 333.804, "duration": 13.09}, {"text": "All of the teachers and students in attendance of these private academies formerly attended or taught in the public school system located adjacent to or in the same vicinity as the private academy.", "start": 333.804, "stop": 349.529, "duration": 15.73}, {"text": "With few exceptions, these academies are all part of a new association called in Mississippi, The Private School Association and with very few exceptions, all are members of a Private Academy Athletic Conference.", "start": 349.529, "stop": 366.108, "duration": 16.58}, {"text": "They’re segregated.", "start": 366.108, "stop": 367.347, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "They were formed in response to public school desegregation.", "start": 367.347, "stop": 370.727, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "They undermine public integrated education.", "start": 370.727, "stop": 375.954, "duration": 5.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Leventhal, if this aid were withdrawn or outlawed, is it your thought these academies would collapse?", "start": 375.954, "stop": 386.178, "duration": 10.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 386.178, "stop": 387.379, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "We can only speculate as to what would occur if this textbook aid were withdrawn.", "start": 387.379, "stop": 393.108, "duration": 5.73}, {"text": "We know it couldn’t help the private academies.", "start": 393.108, "stop": 395.142, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "We know it would be denying them in excess of a half a million dollars in basic inventories and it would be denying them the resources of the State but --", "start": 395.142, "stop": 407.444, "duration": 12.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is the aid amount to per pupil?", "start": 407.444, "stop": 409.924, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "It amounts to six dollars per pupil, Your Honor.", "start": 409.924, "stop": 413.103, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "It amounts to $5000 or $6000 per school.", "start": 413.103, "stop": 416.393, "duration": 3.29}]}, {"speakerName": "William H. Rehnquist", "textObjs": [{"text": "Six dollars per pupil per year?", "start": 416.393, "stop": 418.52, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 418.52, "stop": 419.363, "duration": 0.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you think this would prompt a pupil to go back into the public school?", "start": 419.363, "stop": 424.676, "duration": 5.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, given the finding effect in all of these cases, all of the cases involved in private academies that -- they were formed on the finished financial basis.", "start": 424.676, "stop": 436.425, "duration": 11.75}, {"text": "Given the widespread poverty in the State of Mississippi, it’s not beyond possibility that they will return to public schools if this aid and other aid is withdrawn.", "start": 436.425, "stop": 449.307, "duration": 12.88}, {"text": "Again, its speculative.", "start": 449.307, "stop": 450.435, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "We have to concede that tuition grants, the withdrawal of tuition grants like the Coffey versus State Educational Finance Commission did not result in the return of white students to public integrated schools.", "start": 450.435, "stop": 468.354, "duration": 17.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Lewis F. Powell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did you mention how the aid -- is that other State aid now being provided to these schools?", "start": 468.354, "stop": 477.283, "duration": 8.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor there is presently pending in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Mississippi a suit to prohibit the State’s -- the State public schools of higher education from permitting the private academies the use of the athletic stadiums of our public colleges and universities.", "start": 477.283, "stop": 502.23, "duration": 24.95}, {"text": "There is of course the availability of various state educational agencies and programs which can be used in the State, in private academies of the State.", "start": 502.23, "stop": 515.826, "duration": 13.6}, {"text": "Basically, however, the textbook aid is the outstanding major provision of aid to the private academies by the State of Mississippi at this time.", "start": 515.826, "stop": 527.099, "duration": 11.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what would happen if the aid was withdrawn?", "start": 527.099, "stop": 532.201, "duration": 5.1}, {"text": "Would the parents have to buy the books for the youngsters?", "start": 532.201, "stop": 535.553, "duration": 3.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir or the schools would have to purchase them.", "start": 535.553, "stop": 539.66, "duration": 4.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, as one who is old enough to remember that I had to buy my own books all the time, I wonder how much fact the six dollars per pupil per year is even in Mississippi?", "start": 539.66, "stop": 556.501, "duration": 16.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, if the case is viewed as the provision of six dollars of aid per pupil, it might appear to be de minimis, but since this is a challenge to the provision of State aid, the question is not how much is each child receiving, but how much is the State of Mississippi allocating and distributing to the private schools of the State and it's distributing in excess of a half a million dollars of State money.", "start": 556.501, "stop": 584.748, "duration": 28.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, isn’t it distributing it to the children rather than to the schools?", "start": 584.748, "stop": 589.666, "duration": 4.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we don’t know that that’s relevant in the Fourteenth Amendment context.", "start": 589.666, "stop": 593.995, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "It’s clear that the books are being selected by the school.", "start": 593.995, "stop": 597.226, "duration": 3.23}, {"text": "They’re being stocked by the schools.", "start": 597.226, "stop": 600.72, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "Now, theoretically, the aid is going to the student, but practically speaking, the schools are controlling the program.", "start": 600.72, "stop": 608.092, "duration": 7.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Harry A. Blackmun", "textObjs": [{"text": "But don’t we have cases here that have upheld the supply of textbook aid to pupils attending parochial school?", "start": 608.092, "stop": 616.536, "duration": 8.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, indeed we do, Your Honor and that’s one of the issues raised by this appeal.", "start": 616.536, "stop": 621.122, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "Whether the standard for reviewing state support of parochial schools is comparable to the standard for reviewing state support of racially segregated schools and we submit, of course, that the two amendments are substantially different and we can get to that immediately.", "start": 621.122, "stop": 642.608, "duration": 21.49}, {"text": "The Chief Justice in Walz versus Tax Commission and I quote stated that, “an effort to interpret and understand the establishment or religion clauses of the First Amendment requires that we apply constitutional principles so as to serve,” and I quote, “ultimate constitutional objectives as illuminated by history.”", "start": 642.608, "stop": 668.166, "duration": 25.56}, {"text": "In Walz versus Tax Commission, the Court went on to quote Mr. Justice Douglas and said, “When the state encourages religious instruction, it follows the best of our traditions or then respects the religious nature of our people and accommodates the public service to their spiritual needs.”", "start": 668.166, "stop": 689.77, "duration": 21.6}, {"text": "In other words, under the First Amendment when we look at the history of the religion clauses, we find that their objective was not to eliminate any form of State aid for religious instruction.", "start": 689.77, "stop": 707.098, "duration": 17.33}, {"text": "Instead, we find an internal tension or instead as the Court has observed, we walk a tight rope and we balance the establishment clause against the free exercise clause.", "start": 707.098, "stop": 719.986, "duration": 12.89}, {"text": "Recognize that in terms of our history, religion has served an important function and in terms of the religion clauses, we must strike the balance and protect the individual in his right, his First Amendment right to pursue his religious beliefs.", "start": 719.986, "stop": 738.285, "duration": 18.3}, {"text": "When we turn to the Fourteenth Amendment, Your Honor, we find instead a history marked by a commitment to the elimination of State support for racial discrimination.", "start": 738.285, "stop": 748.019, "duration": 9.73}, {"text": "This is the fundamental difference between any approach to aid in the context of the religion clauses and aid in the context of equal protection.", "start": 748.019, "stop": 759.169, "duration": 11.15}, {"text": "We are as a people committed to recognizing the value of religion in American life.", "start": 759.169, "stop": 765.529, "duration": 6.36}, {"text": "At the same time, we are as a people and as a matter of constitutional principle, committed to the elimination of racial discrimination and the support of racial discrimination by the State.", "start": 765.529, "stop": 777.474, "duration": 11.95}, {"text": "So, it is of no help to us in this case to refer as the District Court did to our First Amendment standard.", "start": 777.474, "stop": 784.357, "duration": 6.88}, {"text": "There are again in the words of the Chief Justice, in the Walz versus Tax Commission, ultimate constitutional objective as illuminated by history in the First Amendment which are diametrically opposed to objective as illuminated by history in the context of the Fourteenth Amendment.", "start": 784.357, "stop": 802.655, "duration": 18.3}, {"text": "The failure of the District Court to recognize this represents the basic fundamental error which we bring to this Court.", "start": 802.655, "stop": 812.693, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "Again, along the same lines, we have since the enactment, the adoption of the Fourteenth Amendment.", "start": 812.693, "stop": 821.829, "duration": 9.14}, {"text": "In our very recent history have civil rights laws enacted by the Congress in 1957, in 1961, in 1964, in 1968 and 1965 and 1968.", "start": 821.829, "stop": 833.832, "duration": 12}, {"text": "All of these legislations, all of the decisions of the Court since Cooper versus Aaron, since Brown versus Board of Education stand for the proposition that the constitutional objective as illuminated by history in the Fourteenth Amendment context is the elimination of any state support for racial discrimination.", "start": 833.832, "stop": 852.785, "duration": 18.95}, {"text": "When the State of Mississippi aligns itself by the provision of a half a million dollars to direct subsidy to private academies which discriminate on the basis of race, it has violated this historical -- the Fourteenth Amendment as illuminated by history.", "start": 852.785, "stop": 869.05, "duration": 16.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you think it makes any difference that the act antedated Brown against The Board of Education by a dozen years or how do you think that bears on the subject?", "start": 869.05, "stop": 881.852, "duration": 12.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, we don’t believe that the absence of a specific purpose to discriminate in anomaly undermines our claim or in any way dilutes or attenuates the State’s duty not to align itself with public, with racial discrimination.", "start": 881.852, "stop": 897.844, "duration": 15.99}, {"text": "In fact, when the statute was passed, we had an absolute dual school system in Mississippi, so the issue could never have arisen in 1942.", "start": 897.844, "stop": 907.196, "duration": 9.35}, {"text": "If anything we know that the legislature of Mississippi in 1942 provided textbook aid for segregated academies or for segregated schools, at that time they were public.", "start": 907.196, "stop": 917.605, "duration": 10.41}, {"text": "This was reminiscent of the problem faced in Brown versus Board of Education where we had no legislative history of the Fourteenth Amendment which revealed the intention of Congress with regard to public education.", "start": 917.605, "stop": 932.066, "duration": 14.46}, {"text": "In fact, there was no public education, said the Court in Brown, at the time of the adoption of the Fourteenth Amendment.", "start": 932.066, "stop": 938.354, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "And given that fact, the Court had to move to other considerations to determine whether there was a violation of equal protection.", "start": 938.354, "stop": 944.78, "duration": 6.43}, {"text": "So, we have a statute passed in 1942 before the problem arose and the question of purpose cannot be pursued in the same way that we would pursue purpose with the specific facts available.", "start": 944.78, "stop": 958.363, "duration": 13.58}, {"text": "In addition to that, the Court --", "start": 958.363, "stop": 961.276, "duration": 2.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "And do you think it contributed to the maintenance of the dual system any more or less in 1942 than in 1972?", "start": 961.276, "stop": 972.185, "duration": 10.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "In 1942, no sir.", "start": 972.185, "stop": 976.184, "duration": 4}, {"text": "In 19 -- well, in 1942, we had a dual school system which was lawful.", "start": 976.184, "stop": 982.453, "duration": 6.27}, {"text": "In 1972, we have a dual school system that is unlawful.", "start": 982.453, "stop": 987.518, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "Now, what is true, Your Honor, in terms of the statute and in terms of the black children of Mississippi and this reminiscent of a woman -- reminiscent of woman in power, It is of no consolation to the black children of Mississippi or the black population of Mississippi that the legislature in 1942 did not intend to promote segregation.", "start": 987.518, "stop": 1011.328, "duration": 23.81}, {"text": "The fact is, the effect of the statute is to promote segregation and that promotion of segregation is the gravamen of our complaint.", "start": 1011.328, "stop": 1020.179, "duration": 8.85}, {"text": "It is of no consolation to the black children that the State does not intend to do something when the evil is there.", "start": 1020.179, "stop": 1028.679, "duration": 8.5}, {"text": "Now, again on this First Amendment or this religion issue versus the Fourteenth Amendment issue, in Green versus Kennedy, another three-judge District Court was faced with the problem of federal tax exemption benefits to the private academies of Mississippi, the same private academies.", "start": 1028.679, "stop": 1054.219, "duration": 25.54}, {"text": "I remind the Court that a tax exemption was an indirect benefit to these private academies, there was significantly less support for racial discrimination in Mississippi’s textbook statute.", "start": 1054.219, "stop": 1068.198, "duration": 13.98}, {"text": "Here we have a direct grant of at least a half a million dollars, or a quarter of a million dollars annually and yet, the three judge District Court affirmed by this Court held that tax exemption is only minimal and remote involvement when compared to the kind of identification in support of religion prohibited by the establishment clause.", "start": 1068.198, "stop": 1089.347, "duration": 21.15}, {"text": "But the governmental and constitutional interest of avoiding racial discrimination in educational institutions embraces the interest to be -- or precludes even indirect economic benefit to racial discrimination.", "start": 1089.347, "stop": 1104.982, "duration": 15.63}, {"text": "Again, it’s juxtaposition of the requirements of the religion clauses versus the requirement of the equal protection clause.", "start": 1104.982, "stop": 1121.012, "duration": 16.03}, {"text": "We are of the clear view that the proper standard for reviewing State support for racially discriminatory educational institutions can be found in Cooper versus Aaron.", "start": 1121.012, "stop": 1136.1, "duration": 15.09}, {"text": "There, this Court held that State support for racial discrimination through any arrangement, through any management or any fund is violative of equal protection.", "start": 1136.1, "stop": 1150.484, "duration": 14.38}, {"text": "When the State of Mississippi provides textbook aid and places itself behind the racial discrimination, and in effect or in fact incurred this racial discrimination, it violates Cooper versus Aaron.", "start": 1150.484, "stop": 1163.603, "duration": 13.12}, {"text": "And our second basic theory is that under the principles of Green versus New Kent County, Virginia, the State has an affirmative duty to promote racially integrated education, that given its support for racial discrimination in the dual school system in the past, it is duty bound today to remove itself entirely from racial discrimination.", "start": 1163.603, "stop": 1185.629, "duration": 22.03}, {"text": "Indeed, it has a duty to quarantine racial discrimination.", "start": 1185.629, "stop": 1190.451, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "Anything less than that would be violative of Green versus New Kent County, Virginia.", "start": 1190.451, "stop": 1197.798, "duration": 7.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Leventhal, your prayer for relief is for a judgment of reversal and a remand of the case with instructions to enter an order enjoining the appellees from distributing textbooks to the private segregated academies of Mississippi.", "start": 1197.798, "stop": 1217.556, "duration": 19.76}, {"text": "And I notice in your footnote six on page seven of your brief, you set out the fact that there were 202 private schools operating in Mississippi during the 1970-71 school years and you could see that 47 of them, being the Catholic schools and seven others being the special schools, I guess, for handicapped people and so on are not, although private, they’re not segregated?", "start": 1217.556, "stop": 1244.059, "duration": 26.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s correct, Your Honor.", "start": 1244.059, "stop": 1247.18, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That seems to leave about 148 that you claim are segregated but that the -- I gather your brothers on the other side say, “Well, no they’re not.", "start": 1247.18, "stop": 1257.46, "duration": 10.28}, {"text": "They’re just -- the tuition is high and they happen to be all white, but they’re not segregated schools.”", "start": 1257.46, "stop": 1263.092, "duration": 5.63}, {"text": "Would it be your thought that with respect to each one of these 148, there had -- there would have to be a separate hearing or what?", "start": 1263.092, "stop": 1271.052, "duration": 7.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, we have conducted -- we -- extensive discovery in this case.", "start": 1271.052, "stop": 1277.473, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "We have 104 deposition in -- depositions in evidence.", "start": 1277.473, "stop": 1281.293, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "We believe that we’ve already made a record against all 148 academies.", "start": 1281.293, "stop": 1285.894, "duration": 4.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "One by one or --?", "start": 1285.894, "stop": 1286.841, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 1286.841, "stop": 1288.184, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "Indeed we have and part of the --", "start": 1288.184, "stop": 1289.511, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the fact that the black -- white zone?", "start": 1289.511, "stop": 1294.033, "duration": 4.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes Your Honor.", "start": 1294.033, "stop": 1294.585, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or what?", "start": 1294.585, "stop": 1295.598, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that they’re segregate --", "start": 1295.598, "stop": 1296.941, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Voice Overlap) Or just to devise to avoid a seg -- a desegregation order?", "start": 1296.941, "stop": 1301.247, "duration": 4.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we have --", "start": 1301.247, "stop": 1301.725, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Byron R. White", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or they are -- they do the -- who would -- they have been on a black person, that’d be applied (Inaudible)", "start": 1301.725, "stop": 1306.237, "duration": 4.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, some have -- some school administrators, private school administrators testified that they had an open enrollment policy.", "start": 1306.237, "stop": 1313.735, "duration": 7.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s what I thought.", "start": 1313.735, "stop": 1314.635, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 1314.635, "stop": 1315.496, "duration": 0.86}, {"text": "They’re a handful of such disputes.", "start": 1315.496, "stop": 1316.982, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what about (Inaudible)", "start": 1316.982, "stop": 1319.063, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we believe that the District Courts concerned and confronted with private academies in Mississippi have already held that all of these academies by segregationist institutions that question of fact.", "start": 1319.063, "stop": 1332.063, "duration": 13}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "In this case?", "start": 1332.063, "stop": 1333.314, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor in -- well, by implication in this case, the extensive findings of fact were not made in this case, but in other cases, in Coffey I and Coffey II, in Green versus Kennedy.", "start": 1333.314, "stop": 1342.008, "duration": 8.69}]}, {"speakerName": "William H. Rehnquist", "textObjs": [{"text": "And what (Voice Overlap) find in this case with respect to this type of allegation, did it pass on them?", "start": 1342.008, "stop": 1347.61, "duration": 5.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "By implication it did.", "start": 1347.61, "stop": 1348.64, "duration": 1.03}, {"text": "It found that they are racially segregated and it considered the issue before the Court as framed by the assumption that they were racially segregated and segregationists that is they had a closed admissions policy that blacks would be excluded.", "start": 1348.64, "stop": 1365.147, "duration": 16.51}]}, {"speakerName": "William H. Rehnquist", "textObjs": [{"text": "They’d assumed this for the sake of argument or did it specifically find that?", "start": 1365.147, "stop": 1368.936, "duration": 3.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "It didn’t make that specific finding.", "start": 1368.936, "stop": 1370.463, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "It assumed it for the purpose of argument, they held --", "start": 1370.463, "stop": 1372.648, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "And held that even on the hypothesis or the assumption that they were segregated, nonetheless, this was a constitutionally valid action on the part of the State.", "start": 1372.648, "stop": 1382.221, "duration": 9.57}, {"text": "But if we should hold in agreement with you that to the extent they are segregated, it’s not constitutionally valid then wouldn’t it be necessary to look at each school?", "start": 1382.221, "stop": 1394.142, "duration": 11.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, on remand, I believe the District Court could look at each school and find in the record sufficient evidence to show that they were segregationists.", "start": 1394.142, "stop": 1401.962, "duration": 7.82}, {"text": "Now, this case involved the taking of numerous depositions of private school administrators who had an ample opportunity to intervene and protect their interests.", "start": 1401.962, "stop": 1413.044, "duration": 11.08}, {"text": "No such private academy intervened.", "start": 1413.044, "stop": 1415.168, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "But several of them did say in your pretrial discovery that, “No, we’re not segregated.", "start": 1415.168, "stop": 1421.637, "duration": 6.47}, {"text": "We’re high priced, but we’re not segregated.”", "start": 1421.637, "stop": 1423.32, "duration": 1.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that’s correct but at the same time, the evidence showed that they were formed at critical moments in critical school districts and that, they were in fact segregated schools.", "start": 1423.32, "stop": 1433.093, "duration": 9.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn’t there are some evidence here about a number, or perhaps a dozen or more Orientals and others in this academy?", "start": 1433.093, "stop": 1443.596, "duration": 10.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, I believe, I’ll give you the exact figure.", "start": 1443.596, "stop": 1451.539, "duration": 7.94}, {"text": "All students are white except for 15 Chinese.", "start": 1451.539, "stop": 1455.358, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "This is what school officials said.", "start": 1455.358, "stop": 1457.182, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "This appears at footnote 3 of appendix A of page 1A.", "start": 1457.182, "stop": 1462.53, "duration": 5.35}, {"text": "All students and all faculty members are white except for 15 Chinese, 16 Orientals, two Indians and two Latin Americans.", "start": 1462.53, "stop": 1469.535, "duration": 7.01}, {"text": "That’s out of a total of 42,000 children.", "start": 1469.535, "stop": 1473.936, "duration": 4.4}, {"text": "There’s not a single black child in any of these academies.", "start": 1473.936, "stop": 1479.792, "duration": 5.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Lewis F. Powell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Were any of the schools that you’ve listed founded and in operation prior to Brown v. Board of Education?", "start": 1479.792, "stop": 1488.687, "duration": 8.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "One or two.", "start": 1488.687, "stop": 1489.647, "duration": 0.96}, {"text": "Not prior to Brown.", "start": 1489.647, "stop": 1491.079, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "Yes, one or two prior to Brown, Your Honor.", "start": 1491.079, "stop": 1493.591, "duration": 2.51}, {"text": "Yes.", "start": 1493.591, "stop": 1494.208, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Lewis F. Powell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1494.208, "stop": 1494.579, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, they could’ve been founded prior to Brown and after Green and Alexander expanded their program to accommodate whites who were plain public integrated schools and to the extent that they opened their doors, added facilities, added grades, they would be demonstrating that they’re segregationist and undermining public integrated education and should therefore be subject to an injunctive order prohibiting textbook aid to them.", "start": 1494.579, "stop": 1525.72, "duration": 31.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Lewis F. Powell, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I know nothing to about Mississippi, but there are some private schools up and down East Coast that are not segregated and never have been.", "start": 1525.72, "stop": 1537.583, "duration": 11.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor, that’s certainly possible.", "start": 1537.583, "stop": 1539.631, "duration": 2.05}, {"text": "Again, we’re not claiming that all private schools should not receive textbooks.", "start": 1539.631, "stop": 1544.988, "duration": 5.36}, {"text": "Our claim is that a specific type of private academy should not be receiving that.", "start": 1544.988, "stop": 1549.737, "duration": 4.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "How would you define that type?", "start": 1549.737, "stop": 1551.488, "duration": 1.75}, {"text": "One --", "start": 1551.488, "stop": 1551.64, "duration": 0.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "It’s a private school formed for the purpose or having the effect of providing white students with an alternative to public integrated education.", "start": 1551.64, "stop": 1559.401, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that’s true about any private school, isn’t it?", "start": 1559.401, "stop": 1562.733, "duration": 3.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 1562.733, "stop": 1563.179, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "Not necessarily.", "start": 1563.179, "stop": 1564.971, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "It would be true of virtually every private school in the State of Mississippi, but I’m referring to the questions raised by Mr. Justice Powell about the East Coast of the United States.", "start": 1564.971, "stop": 1576.505, "duration": 11.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Potter Stewart", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, let’s assume a private school has been existence for 50 years, that’s very, very high priced and that’s always been all white, but which would welcome, in fact, would welcome and be delighted to have Negro students.", "start": 1576.505, "stop": 1591.61, "duration": 15.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "They wouldn’t be covered, Your Honor.", "start": 1591.61, "stop": 1593.175, "duration": 1.57}, {"text": "You see, the academy I’m speaking of had substantially expanded its enrollment at key moments and these are -- in other words, an academy formed in 1945 which enrolled 200 pupils and served grades one through four, through the year 1968, Green.", "start": 1593.175, "stop": 1609.961, "duration": 16.79}, {"text": "And then in 1968, expanded its enrollment to 1000 white students and served grades one through 12 would be a school which was undermining public integrated education.", "start": 1609.961, "stop": 1620.855, "duration": 10.89}]}, {"speakerName": "William H. Rehnquist", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the kind of school Mr. Justice Stewart described if you simply apply your effect test would have the same result.", "start": 1620.855, "stop": 1628.04, "duration": 7.18}, {"text": "It could exist in Massachusetts and maybe white people in Mississippi who don’t want their kids to go to integrated schools would send -- send their kid up there, knowing that he would not be integrated if you’re up at this particular place in Massachusetts.", "start": 1628.04, "stop": 1642.103, "duration": 14.06}, {"text": "Now, that meets your effect definition, it seems to me.", "start": 1642.103, "stop": 1643.839, "duration": 1.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I’m talking about an effect principle which I’m prepared to limit to a formal -- formally de jure school system or State which operated a de jure system of public school, de jure segregated system of public education which subsequently -- subsequent to the integral -- substantial integration of schools experienced a loss, a substantial loss of white pupils who are presently attending the segregated academy.", "start": 1643.839, "stop": 1674.37, "duration": 30.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "But if to pursue Justice Stewart’s hypothetical, it would demonstrate that in fact they had an open admissions policy and would accept a Negro who could pay the tuition, would you say that because the effect was deleterious, it falls under this ban?", "start": 1674.37, "stop": 1694.572, "duration": 20.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, we would submit that in the State of Mississippi, an open admissions policy would return the State to freedom of choice.", "start": 1694.572, "stop": 1701.784, "duration": 7.21}, {"text": "The classic example in the city of Jackson where we have lost 40,000, excuse me, 40% of the white students, we have white citizen's council schools assuming that the white citizens council adopted an open admissions policy and let’s assume further that the very remote possibility that blacks would attend the white citizen’s council school came to pass, we would have the white citizens council still undermining public integrated education.", "start": 1701.784, "stop": 1732.461, "duration": 30.68}]}, {"speakerName": "William H. Rehnquist", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you’re saying in effect then that in Mississippi, children have to go to public schools?", "start": 1732.461, "stop": 1738.191, "duration": 5.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 1738.191, "stop": 1738.591, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "I’m saying that if that what --", "start": 1738.591, "stop": 1739.354, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "William H. Rehnquist", "textObjs": [{"text": "That’s what it amounts to, isn’t it?", "start": 1739.354, "stop": 1741.271, "duration": 1.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Melvyn R. Leventhal", "textObjs": [{"text": "I’m saying that if they want to go to private schools, they ought to do so without State’s support.(Voice Overlap)", "start": 1741.271, "stop": 1748.385, "duration": 7.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Warren E. Burger", "textObjs": [{"text": "We will resume at this point in the morning, counsel.", "start": 1748.385, "stop": 1753.333, "duration": 4.95}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Burger Court", "arguedOn": "Feb  20 - 21, 1973", "petitioner": "", "respondent": "", "docket": "72-77", "citation": "413 US 455 (1973)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/413/455", "lowerCourt": "", "grantedOn": "", "decidedOn": "Jun 25, 1973", "wikiData": {"title": "Norwood v. Harrison", "Litigants": "Norwood v. Harrison", "ArgueDateA": "February 20", "ArgueDateB": "21", "ArgueYear": "1973", "DecideDate": "June 25", "DecideYear": "1973", "FullName": "Norwood, et al. v. Harrison, et al.", "USVol": "413", "USPage": "455", "ParallelCitations": "93 S. Ct. 2804; 37 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 723; 1973 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 28", "Prior": "340 [[F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/340/1003/1445529/ 1003] ([[N.D. Miss.]] 1972)", "Subsequent": "On remand, 382 [[F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/382/921/2596923/ 921] (N.D. Miss. 1974); attorneys' fees awarded, 410 [[F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/410/133/2308409/ 133] (N.D. Miss. 1976); affirmed, 581 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/581/518/279539/ 518] ([[5th Cir.]] 1978)", "Holding": "Private schools have the right to exist and to operate, but the State is not required by the Equal Protection Clause to provide assistance to private schools equivalent to that it provides to public schools without regard to whether the private schools discriminate on racial grounds.", "SCOTUS": "1972-1975", "Majority": "Burger", "JoinMajority": "Stewart, White, Marshall, Blackmun, Powell, Rehnquist", "Concurrence": "Douglas", "Concurrence2": "Brennan", "LawsApplied": ""}}